{"title_page": "Massacre of Wassy", "text_new": "[[File:Massacre de Vassy 1562 print by Hogenberg end of 16th century.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|''Massacre de Vassy'' in 1562, print by Hogenberg end of 16th century.]]\n{{Campaignbox French Wars of Religion}}\n\nThe '''Massacre of Wassy''', also known as the '''Massacre of Vassy''', is the name given to the murder of [[Huguenot]] worshippers and citizens in an armed action by troops of [[Francis, Duke of Guise]], in [[Wassy]], [[France]] on 1 March 1562. The massacre is identified as the first major event in the [[French Wars of Religion]]. The series of battles that followed concluded in the signing of the [[Edict of Amboise| Peace of Amboise]] (or Pacification Treaty of Amboise) the next year, on 19 March 1563.\n\nThe events surrounding the Massacre of Wassy became widely known by a series of forty [[engraving]]s published in [[Geneva]] seven years later.<ref>Jean Ehrmann, \"Massacre and Persecution Pictures in Sixteenth Century France\" in ''Journal of the Warburg and Courtauld Institutes'', vol. 8, (1945), London: The Warburg Institute, pp. 195-199</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{unsourced|section|date=February 2017}}\nAfter the ascent of [[Henry II of France|Henry II]] to the French throne, followers of the religious teachings of [[John Calvin]], known as Huguenots, were persecuted in France. [[Catherine de' Medici]], regent of [[Charles IX of France|Charles IX]], proposed the [[Edict of January]] (or [[Edict of Saint-Germain]]) with the hopes that [[Calvinism]] and [[Catholicism]] could co-exist in France and that fighting would cease...\n\n===Massacre===\nOn 1 March 1562, [[Francis, Duke of Guise|Francis (Fran\u00e7ois)]], the second [[Duke of Guise]], travelling to his estates, stopped in [[Wassy]] (aka Vassy) and decided to attend Mass. He found a large congregation of [[Huguenots]] holding religious ceremonies in a barn that was their church. Some of the duke's party attempted to push their way inside and were repulsed. Events escalated, stones began to fly, and the Duke was struck. Outraged, he ordered his men to fortify the town and set fire to the church, killing 63 unarmed Huguenots and wounding over a hundred.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lindsay|first=Thomas M.|title=History of the Reformation Reformation in Switzerland, France, the Netherlands, Scotland and England|page=189|year=2003|origyear=1906|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons; Kessinger Publishing|isbn=978-0-7661-6367-6|oclc=3960339|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KjPtkNc7YDIC&pg=PA189|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\n{{onesource|date=February 2017}}\nThe [[massacre]] provoked open hostilities between some followers of each religion, sparking the first war of a long series of [[French Wars of Religion]], which continued largely uninterrupted for more than a century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Justo L.|title=The Story of Christianity: The Reformation to the present day|year=2010|publisher=Zondervan|isbn=978-0-06-185589-4|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=apDhc1QpprMC&pg=PA128|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Bourbons, led by the [[Louis I de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Prince of Cond\u00e9]], and proclaiming that they were liberating the king and regent from \"evil\" councillors, organised a kind of protectorate over the Protestant churches and began to seize and garrison strategic towns along the [[Loire]]. Although the Huguenots had begun to mobilise for war before Vassy,<ref>Knecht, The French Civil Wars, p86</ref> [[Louis I de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]] used the massacre as evidence that the Edict had been broken, lending further weight to his campaign, and as hostilities broke out, the Edict was in fact revoked under pressure from the Guise faction.\n\nThe major engagements of the war occurred at [[Rouen]], [[Battle of Dreux|Dreux]] and Orl\u00e9ans. At the Siege of Rouen (May\u2013October 1562), the crown regained the city at the cost of [[Antoine de Bourbon, duc de Vend\u00f4me|Antoine de Navarre]], who died of his wounds. The Battle of Dreux (December 1562), saw the capture of [[Louis I de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]] by the Guises and [[Anne de Montmorency|Montmorency]], the governor general, by the Bourbons. \n\nIn February 1563, at the Siege of Orl\u00e9ans, [[Francis, Duke of Guise]] was shot and killed by the Huguenot Poltrot de M\u00e9r\u00e9; the Guise considered this an [[assassination]] on the orders of the duke\u2019s enemy, [[Gaspard II de Coligny|Admiral Coligny]], as it was outside of direct combat. The popular unrest caused by the 'assassination', coupled with the fact that [[Orl\u00e9ans]] was holding out in the siege, led [[Catherine de' Medici|Catherine]] to mediate a truce and the [[Edict of Amboise]] (1563).\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of massacres in France]]\n*[[St. Bartholomew's Day massacre|St. Bartholomew's Day Massacre]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/the-protestant-museum-in-the-wassy-barn/ Virtual Museum of Protestantism: ''The protestant Museum in the Wassy barn'']\n\n{{coord missing|France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Massacre Of Vassy}}\n[[Category:1562 in France]]\n[[Category:Anti-Protestantism]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1562]]\n[[Category:Massacres in France|Wassy]]\n[[Category:History of Haute-Marne]]\n[[Category:French Wars of Religion]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Massacre de Vassy 1562 print by Hogenberg end of 16th century.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|''Massacre de Vassy'' in 1562, print by Hogenberg end of 16th century.]]\n{{Campaignbox French Wars of Religion}}\n\nThe '''Massacre of Wassy''', also known as the '''Massacre of Vassy''', is the name given to the murder of [[Huguenot]] worshippers and citizens in an armed action by troops of [[Francis, Duke of Guise]], in [[Wassy]], [[France]] on 1 March 1562. The massacre is identified as the first major event in the [[French Wars of Religion]]. The series of battles that followed concluded in the signing of the [[Edict of Amboise| Peace of Amboise]] (or Pacification Treaty of Amboise) the next year, on 19 March 1563.\n\nThe events surrounding the Massacre of Wassy became widely known by a series of forty [[engraving]]s published in [[Geneva]] seven years later.<ref>Jean Ehrmann, \"Massacre and Persecution Pictures in Sixteenth Century France\" in ''Journal of the Warburg and Courtauld Institutes'', vol. 8, (1945), London: The Warburg Institute, pp. 195-199</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{unsourced|section|date=February 2017}}\nAfter the ascent of [[Henry II of France|Henry II]] to the French throne, followers of the religious teachings of [[John Calvin]], known as Huguenots, were persecuted in France. [[Catherine de' Medici]], regent of [[Charles IX of France|Charles IX]], proposed the [[Edict of January]] (or [[Edict of Saint-Germain]]) with the hopes that [[Calvinism]] and [[Catholicism]] could co-exist in France and that fighting would cease.\n\n===Massacre===\nOn 1 March 1562, [[Francis, Duke of Guise|Francis (Fran\u00e7ois)]], the second [[Duke of Guise]], travelling to his estates, stopped in [[Wassy]] (aka Vassy) and decided to attend Mass. He found a large congregation of [[Huguenots]] holding religious ceremonies in a barn that was their church. Some of the duke's party attempted to push their way inside and were repulsed. Events escalated, stones began to fly, and the Duke was struck. Outraged, he ordered his men to fortify the town and set fire to the church, killing 63 unarmed Huguenots and wounding over a hundred.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lindsay|first=Thomas M.|title=History of the Reformation Reformation in Switzerland, France, the Netherlands, Scotland and England|page=189|year=2003|origyear=1906|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons; Kessinger Publishing|isbn=978-0-7661-6367-6|oclc=3960339|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KjPtkNc7YDIC&pg=PA189|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\n{{onesource|date=February 2017}}\nThe [[massacre]] provoked open hostilities between some followers of each religion, sparking the first war of a long series of [[French Wars of Religion]], which continued largely uninterrupted for more than a century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Justo L.|title=The Story of Christianity: The Reformation to the present day|year=2010|publisher=Zondervan|isbn=978-0-06-185589-4|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=apDhc1QpprMC&pg=PA128|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Bourbons, led by the [[Louis I de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Prince of Cond\u00e9]], and proclaiming that they were liberating the king and regent from \"evil\" councillors, organised a kind of protectorate over the Protestant churches and began to seize and garrison strategic towns along the [[Loire]]. Although the Huguenots had begun to mobilise for war before Vassy,<ref>Knecht, The French Civil Wars, p86</ref> [[Louis I de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]] used the massacre as evidence that the Edict had been broken, lending further weight to his campaign, and as hostilities broke out, the Edict was in fact revoked under pressure from the Guise faction.\n\nThe major engagements of the war occurred at [[Rouen]], [[Battle of Dreux|Dreux]] and Orl\u00e9ans. At the Siege of Rouen (May\u2013October 1562), the crown regained the city at the cost of [[Antoine de Bourbon, duc de Vend\u00f4me|Antoine de Navarre]], who died of his wounds. The Battle of Dreux (December 1562), saw the capture of [[Louis I de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]] by the Guises and [[Anne de Montmorency|Montmorency]], the governor general, by the Bourbons. \n\nIn February 1563, at the Siege of Orl\u00e9ans, [[Francis, Duke of Guise]] was shot and killed by the Huguenot Poltrot de M\u00e9r\u00e9; the Guise considered this an [[assassination]] on the orders of the duke\u2019s enemy, [[Gaspard II de Coligny|Admiral Coligny]], as it was outside of direct combat. The popular unrest caused by the 'assassination', coupled with the fact that [[Orl\u00e9ans]] was holding out in the siege, led [[Catherine de' Medici|Catherine]] to mediate a truce and the [[Edict of Amboise]] (1563).\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of massacres in France]]\n*[[St. Bartholomew's Day massacre|St. Bartholomew's Day Massacre]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/the-protestant-museum-in-the-wassy-barn/ Virtual Museum of Protestantism: ''The protestant Museum in the Wassy barn'']\n\n{{coord missing|France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Massacre Of Vassy}}\n[[Category:1562 in France]]\n[[Category:Anti-Protestantism]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1562]]\n[[Category:Massacres in France|Wassy]]\n[[Category:History of Haute-Marne]]\n[[Category:French Wars of Religion]]\n", "name_user": "186.168.155.153", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massacre_of_Wassy"}
